3. Contract Philosophy

The transformation layer follows:

Events describe reality. Scenes describe experience.

Example:

The HXT layer says:

{
"event":"queen_capture",
"piece":"white_queen",
"target":"black_rook"
}

The HCE layer decides:

{
"scene":"queen_execution",

"story":{
"emotion":"dominance",
"narrative":"decisive victory"
},

"animation":{
"action":"ultimate_strike"
}
}
4. HXT Input Contract
4.1 HXT Event Object

Every cinematic transformation begins from an HXT event.

Schema:

{
"event_id":"evt_0001",

"timestamp":14.5,

"move_number":23,

"side":"white",

"piece":{
"type":"queen",
"square":"h7"
},

"action":{
"type":"capture",
"target":"rook"
},

"analysis":{
"evaluation_change":3.8,
"importance":"high",
"tactical":true
}
}
5. Required HXT Fields
Field	Required	Description
event_id	Yes	Unique event identifier
timestamp	Yes	Timeline position
side	Yes	White / Black
piece	Yes	Acting entity
action	Yes	Chess action
analysis	Yes	Strategic importance
6. Supported HXT Events

Version 1:

Event	Description
movement	Standard movement
capture	Piece elimination
check	King threat
checkmate	Victory condition
promotion	Piece evolution
castle	Defensive reposition
sacrifice	Intentional loss
blunder	Tactical failure
7. Transformation Pipeline

The Cinematic Engine processes HXT events through five stages.

Stage 1 — Event Classification

Input:

{
"action":"capture"
}

Output:

{
"classification":
"combat_event",

"severity":
"medium"
}
Stage 2 — Character Resolution

Maps chess entities into cinematic characters.

Input:

{
"type":"queen"
}

Output:

{
"class":
"legendary_fighter",

"role":
"damage_dealer"
}
Stage 3 — Combat Mapping

Transforms chess mechanics into combat actions.

Example:

{
"capture":
"rook"
}

becomes:

{
"action":
"execution_strike"
}
Stage 4 — Scene Generation

Combines:

event importance
emotion
game state
character identity

into a cinematic scene.

Stage 5 — HCE Assembly

Produces renderer-ready cinematic instructions.

